<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-11-11T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-11-11T11:00:00-05:00" n="721" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d721">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/7660: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The High Commissioner at Constantinople</hi>
                                    (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bristol</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Constantinople</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-11-11T18:00:00+02:00"><hi rend="italic">November 11, 1920—6
                                    p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received November 12—3:21
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>569. Reference McCully’s 88 of November 10th, 4 p.m. This dispatch
                                evidently refers to authority for High Commission to furnish aid
                                with funds, because every possible aid is being given Admiral
                                McCully, likewise all American interests in Crimea, by using naval
                                vessels and every other means I legally can employ.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Bristol</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>